We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
Properly plan, closely monitor, and evaluate the implementation of the identified and prioritized development Programs/Projects/Activities (PPAs) funded by the 20% Development Fund (DF), so that any cause of suspension or problems that would delay the project implementation would be immediately addressed and more desired benefits could be delivered to the constituents this time of pandemic;
Prepare and specifically describe the projects for inclusion in the Annual Investment Plan that partakes the nature of investments and capital expenditure in the 20% DF. Also, include specific and identifiable PPAs related to COVID-19 situation as authorized that have undergone priority ranking by the Local Development Council in terms of urgency and necessity/need which are attainable within the desired time frame in order to maximize the allocated scarce funds to have an immediate impact on the socio-economic development and health/COVID-19 response activity;
Review unimplemented PPAs and ascertain viability of implementation, otherwise, realign or reprogram for more viable and significant PPAs in accordance with the socio-economic development, environmental management and disaster response requirements provided by DILG and DBM JMC No. 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017 and DILG and DBM JMC No. 01 dated March 27, 2020; and
Strictly adhere to the provisions of the DILG and DBM JMC No. 2017-1 in formulating PPAs in order to achieve the maximum benefits for its constituents.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
Direct the Municipal Assessor comply with the provisions of Section 472 of the Local Government Code and Manual on Real Property Appraisal and Assessment Operations and do the tax mapping activity, ocular inspection and other relevant functions of the said office as often as required therein;
The Municipal Assessor submit updated Report on Assessment to the Provincial Assessor’s Office to provide them an accurate information relevant to their plan for a possible general revision of real property assessments every three years and furnish the Municipal Treasurer’s Office with the updated and accurate data on Real Property Tax Account Register which will serve as basis for RPT target and collection every year.
The Municipal Treasurer prepare a duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant to serve as basis in setting up the beginning balances of RPT and SET Receivables and Deferred RPT and SET Income in the books of the Municipality; and
The Municipal Treasurer and Accountant conduct reconciliation of records to establish a realistic balance of Receivables from Real Property Taxes and Special Education Taxes so that necessary adjustment(s) in the books of accounts can be effected for fair presentation of balances in the financial statements;

Review the lease contract on rates of rental and make the necessary action/ amendment to align with the Municipal Tax Ordinance;

Exert more effort in collecting delinquent rental fees and issue notices of demand for rental payments inclusive of penalties from all delinquent market stallholders as soon as the payment falls due in accordance with its power to create sources of revenue; and

Henceforth, strictly implement the pertinent provisions of Municipal Tax Ordinance          No. 12-001 and Republic Act No. 7160.

Exert efforts in the reconstruction of records, verification, validation and analysis of the dormant receivable accounts to effect the necessary adjusting/correcting entries in the books of the Municipality; 

Enforce collection by issuing/follow up demand letters to Hog Dispersal beneficiaries;

Request for write-off from the Commission on Audit the account balances which were considered dormant and could no longer be collected and those that are considered unaccounted; and

Upon approval of request for write-off from the Commission on Audit, prepare the necessary adjusting/ correcting entries in the books of the Municipality to fairly present the receivable accounts in the financial statements.

Attach serially numbered and duly accomplished driver’s trip ticket to support payment made for the procurement of fuel, oil and lubricants;

Require Statement of Account/Bill from the supplier showing the date and total number of liters purchased as well as the price per liter and the total amount due for payment in order to verify the correct amount payable; and 

Henceforth, strictly comply with Commission on Audit (COA) Circular No. 75-6 dated November 7, 1975 and Section 4 (6) of Presidential Decree (P.D.) No. 1445.

Expedite the execution of 20% Development projects identified in the Annual Investment Plan so that more desirable benefits could be delivered to the constituents as planned; 



Review unimplemented programs and projects and ascertain the validity of implementation, otherwise, reprogram for a more relevant and significant PPA as provided by DILG and DBM Circular No. 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017; and 

Strictly adhere to the provisions of the DILG and DBM JMC No. 2017-1 in formulating PPAs in order to achieve the maximum benefits for its constituents.

